{"parse":{"title":"tomato","pageid":3607,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|tomàto|tōmato|tōm̧ato}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n[[File:Tomato Solanum lycopersicum (15806140083).jpg|thumb|a tomato ({{senseno|en|Q23501}})]]\n[[File:Tomato.jpg|thumb|a tomato ({{senseno|en|Q20638126}})]]\n[[File:Lufa Farms Beefsteak Tomato.jpg|thumb|a sliced tomato ({{senseno|en|Q20638126}}) next to a whole one]]\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|en|tomatoe||archaic|now|nonstandard}}\n* {{alter|en|tomater||eye dialect}}\n* {{alter|en|'mater||Southern US|Appalachia|informal}}\n\n===Etymology===\nVariant of earlier {{m|en|tomate}}, from {{bor|en|es|tomate}}, from {{der|en|nci|tomatl}}, from {{der|en|azc-nah-pro|*toma-|*toma-tl}}. Compare {{m|es|tomatillo}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/təˈmɑː.təʊ/|a=RP,AU}}\n** {{audio|en|en-uk-tomato.ogg|a=UK|IPA=[tʰə̥ˈmɑːtʰəʉ̯]}}\n** {{audio|en|En-au-tomato.ogg|a=AU|IPA=[tʰə̥ˈmɐːtʰɐʉ̯]}}\n* {{IPA|en|/təˈmeɪ.toʊ/|a=US}}, {{q|colloquial, sometimes}} {{IPAchar|/təˈmeɪ.tə/}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-tomato.ogg|a=California}}\n* {{IPA|en|[tʰəˈmeɪɾo]|[tʰəˈme(ː)to(ː)]|[tʰɵ-]|[-ma-]|a=CA}}\n* {{IPA|en|/ʈɵˈmaʈo/|/ʈɵˈmɑʈo/|/ʈɵˈmeʈo/|a=Indic}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɑːtəʊ|eɪtəʊ|ætəʊ|s=3}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~|es}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q23501}} A widely [[cultivated]] [[plant]], {{taxfmt|Solanum lycopersicum|species}}, having [[edible]] [[fruit]].\n# {{senseid|en|Q20638126}} The savory [[fruit]] of this plant, most often red when ripe, treated as a [[vegetable]] in [[horticulture]] and [[cooking]].\n#: {{ux|en| He was chopping a '''tomato''' to put in the salad.}}\n#: {{ux|en| He was eating a '''tomato''' when his boss called him.}}\n#: {{syn|en|golden apple|q1=archaic|love apple|q2=archaic|wolf's peach|q3=obsolete|tomater|mato|mater}}\n#: {{meronyms|en|lycopene}}\n#* '''1990''', ''JSG Trading Corp. v. Tray-Wrap, Inc.'', 917 F.2d 75 (2d Cir. 1990)\n#*: In common parlance '''tomatoes''' are vegetables, as the Supreme Court observed long ago [see ''Nix v. Hedden'' 149 U.S. 304, 307, 13 S.Ct. 881, 882, 37 L.Ed. 745 (1893)], although botanically speaking they are actually a fruit. [''26 Encyclopedia Americana'' 832 (Int'l. ed. 1981)]. Regardless of classification, people have been enjoying '''tomatoes''' for centuries; even Mr. Pickwick, as Dickens relates, ate his chops in \"tomata\" sauce.\n# {{senseid|en|Q6592940}} A shade of [[red]], the colour typical of a ripe tomato.\n#: {{color panel|FF6347}}\n# {{senseid|en|physically attractive woman}} {{lb|en|slang}} An attractive [[woman]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=April 4, 1999|author=Frank Decaro|authorlink=Frank DeCaro|title=No Longer the Punch-Line State|work=The New York Times|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/04/style/no-longer-punch-line-state-lauryn-hill-sopranos-others-are-unapologetic-new.html|section=9|page=1|text=Deborah Harry, the New Wave goddess, is finally admitting -- after all the peroxide and posturing of the 1970's and 80's -- that she's really just a <nowiki>''</nowiki>'''tomato'''<nowiki>''</nowiki> (her word) from Paterson {{...}}.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=Denny Durbin|title=Lazy Enchiladas: Redefining Success: Tasty Lessons on Love, Life, & Relationships|publisher=Bodega Publishing|isbn=9780980207248|page=13\n|passage=When she left the room, I asked Robert, “Who&#39;s the '''tomato'''?” “Marisa. She&#39;s from Mexico.” He had a telltale smile on his face.}}\n#* '''2015''' [https://www.bustle.com/articles/116384-19-old-fashioned-compliments-we-should-bring-back 19 Old-Fashioned Compliments We Should Bring Back]\n#*: That shirt makes you look like such a glorious '''tomato'''.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2020|author=Libba Bray|title=The King of Crows|publisher=Little, Brown Books for Young Readers|isbn=9780316532624\n|passage=“Who&#39;s the '''tomato'''?” a cop said as Evie walked past. “Her? She&#39;s the stiff&#39;s niece,” another cop answered.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2025|author={{w|Thomas Pynchon}}|title=Shadow Ticket|publisher=Jonathan Cape|page=19|passage=When did this happen last, a '''tomato''' he's hardly met going to so much trouble? Ever?}}\n# {{lb|en|slang}} A stupid act or person.\n\n====Hypernyms====\n* [[Thesaurus:fruit|fruit]], [[Thesaurus:vegetable|vegetable]] ''(see [[w:tomato#Fruit or vegetable|tomato § Fruit or vegetable]]'')\n** {{l|en|berry}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|clamato|pomato|potomato|Sacratomato|tomacco|tomatine|tomatini|tomatoey|tomatoless|tomatolike|tomatoness|tomatophile|tomtato\n|bitter tomato|mock tomato|clamato|pomato|potomato|Sacratomato|tomacco|tomatine|tomatini|tomatoey|tomatoless|tomatolike|tomatoness|tomatophile|tomtato\n|bush tomato|currant tomato|Datterini tomato|desert tomato|heritage tomato|husk tomato|Italian tomato|strawberry tomato|tomato concentrate|tomato frog|tomato gall|tomato knife|tomato moth|tomato pie|tomato water|tomato worm|tomato-phile\n|beef tomato<ll:UK>\n|beefsteak tomato<ll:US>\n|cherry tomato\n|grape tomato|cocktail tomato|pear tomato|teardrop tomato|tomato clownfish|tomato hornworm|tomato salad|tomato-y\n|plum tomato\n|heirloom tomato\n|Italian tomato|tomato fever|tomato flu\n|Italian plum tomato\n|Roma tomato|tomato sandwich|tomato fruitworm\n|canned tomatoes\n|diced tomatoes|porcupine tomato\n|puréed tomatoes\n|strained tomatoes\n|{{taxlink|Tomato blistering mosaic tymovirus|species}}\n|tomato can\n|tomato juice\n|tomato paste\n|tomato purée\n|tomato sauce\n|tomato surprise\n|tomayto, tomahto|tomato cage|tomato sphinx|tree tomato\n|topepo\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|tomatillo}}\n\n====Descendants====\n{{top3}}\n* {{desc|ny|tomato|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nl|tomaat|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|eo|tomato|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|haw|komako|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|inc-hnd|-|bor=1}}\n** {{desc|hi|टमाटर}}\n** {{desc|ur|ٹماٹر}}\n* {{desctree|ja|トマト|tr=tomato|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|csb|tymatus|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|ko|토마토|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|mi|tōmato|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sw|tomato|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|tpi|tomato}}\n* {{desc|cy|tomato|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|gd|tomàto|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|yo|tòmátì|bor=1}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|tomato plant}}\n* Afrikaans: {{t|af|tamatie}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|طَمَاطِم|f}}, {{t|ar|بَنَدُورَة|f}}\n*: Algerian Arabic: {{t|arq|طوماطيش|tr=ṭōmāṭēš}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|طماطم|f|tr=ṭamaṭem}}\n*: Hijazi Arabic: {{t|acw|طماطم|f|tr=ṭamāṭim}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|ماطيشة|tr=māṭīša}}\n*: South Levantine Arabic: {{t|ajp|بندورة|tr=bandōra}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Assyrian Neo-Aramaic: {{t|aii|ܛܵܡܵܛܵܐ|tr=ṭamaṭa|m}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|tomate|m}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|pomidor}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|помидор}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|домат|m}}\n* Catalan: {{t|ca|tomaquera|f}}\n* Chechen: {{t|ce|бадаржан стом}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|番茄|tr=faan1 ke4-2}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|西紅柿}}, {{t+|cmn|番茄}}, {{t+|cmn|柿子}} {{q|dialectal}}\n* Crimean Tatar: {{t|crh|pamidor}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|rajče|n}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|tomat}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|tomaat|f}}, {{t|nl|tomatenplant|f}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|tomato}}, {{t|eo|tomatujo}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|tomaatti}}, {{t|fi|tomaattikasvi}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|tomate|f}}, {{t+|fr|tomatier|m}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|tomateira|f}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Tomate|f}}, {{t+|de|Tomatenpflanze|f}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ντοματιά|f}}\n* Gujarati: {{t+|gu|ટામેટું|n}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|टमाटर|m}}, {{t+|hi|विलायती|m|tr=vilāyatī}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|paradicsom}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|tómatjurt|f}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|tomatiero}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|tomat}}\n* Irish: {{t+|ga|tráta|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pomodoro|m}}, {{t+|it|pomidoro|m}}, {{t+|it|pummarola|f}} {{qualifier|Naples}}, {{t|it|pommarola|f}} {{qualifier|Naples}}, {{t+|it|tomato|m}} {{qualifier|rare}}, {{t+|it|tomate|m}} {{qualifier|rare}}, {{t+|it|tomata|f}} {{qualifier|Liguria}}, {{t|it|tomatica|f}} {{qualifier|Piedmont}}, {{t|it|pomatica|f}} {{qualifier|Piedmont}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|トマト|tr=tomato}}\n* Kashmiri: {{t+|ks|رُوانٛگُن}}, {{t+|ks|ٹَماٹَر}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|қызанақ}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|k