{{t+|ml|തക്കാളി}}\n* Maltese: {{t+|mt|tadam|m}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|tōmato}}\n* Marathi: {{t+|mr|टोमॅटो}}\n* Mari:\n*: Eastern Mari: {{t|mhr|помидор}}, {{t|mhr|томат}}\n*: Western Mari: {{t|mrj|помидор}}, {{t|mrj|томат}}\n* Mirandese: {{t|mwl|tomate}}, {{t|mwl|tomato}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|mn|улаан лооль}} {{qualifier|official}}, {{t|mn|помидор|}} {{qualifier|popular}}, {{t|mn|төвд хаш|}} {{qualifier|China}}\n*: Mongolian script: {{t|mn|ᠤᠯᠠᠭᠠᠨ ᠯᠣᠣᠯᠢ}}, {{t|mn|ᠫᠣᠮᠢᠳᠣᠷ}}, {{t|mn|ᠲᠥᠪᠦᠳ ᠬᠠᠰᠢ}}\n* Nahuatl:\n*: Central Huasteca Nahuatl: {{t|nch|tomatl}}\n*: Central Nahuatl: {{t|nhn|xihtomatl}}\n*: Classical Nahuatl: {{t|nci|xitomatl}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|chʼil łichxíʼí}}\n* Neapolitan: {{t|nap|pummarola|f}}, {{t|nap|pommarola|f}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|tonmate|f}} {{q|Jersey}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|tomat|m}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|tomat|m}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|tomata|f}}\n* Oriya: {{t|or|ଟମାଟୋ}}\n* Ossetian: {{t|os|пъамидор}}\n* Pannonian Rusyn: {{t|rsk|парадича|f}}\n* Pashto: {{t|ps|رومي|m|tr=rūmi}}, {{t|ps|بانجان|m|tr=bānjān}}, {{t|ps|باتينګړ|m|tr=bātingaṛ}}, {{t+|ps|بادنجان|m|tr=bādanjān}} {{qualifier|also eggplant}}, {{t|ps|رومي بانجان|m|tr=romi bānjān}}, {{t|ps|ټماټر|m|tr=ṭamāṭər}}, {{t|ps|سورباټينګړ|m|tr=surbāṭingaṛ}}, {{t|ps|باټينګن|m|tr=bāṭingən}}\n* Persian:\n*: Dari: {{t|prs|سُرْخِ بَادِمْجَان}}, {{t|prs|بَادِنْجَانِ رومِی}}\n*: Iranian Persian: {{t|fa-ira|گُوْجِه‌فَرَنْگی}}, {{t|fa-ira|گُوْجِه}} {{qualifier|slang}}, {{t|fa-ira|تُمات}} {{qualifier|rare}}\n* Piedmontese: {{t|pms|tomatica|f}}, {{t|pms|pomatica|f}}\n* Pipil: {{t|ppl|tumat}}\n* Plautdietsch: {{t|pdt|Bockelzhonn|f}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|pomidor|m-an}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|tomate|m}}\n* Punjabi: {{t|pa|ਟਮਾਟਰ|m}}, {{t+|pa|ਟਮਾਟਾ}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|chilltu}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|roșie|f}}, {{t+|ro|tomată|f}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|tomata|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|помидо́р|m}}, {{t+|ru|тома́т|m}} {{qualifier|usually processed}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{t|se|tomáhtta}}\n* Samoan: {{t|sm|tamato}}\n* Samogitian: {{t|sgs|puomidors|m}}\n* Sardinian: {{t|sc|tomata|f}}, {{t|sc|pumatta|f}} {{q|Logudorese}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|tomàto|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|пара̀дајз|m}} {{qualifier|Bosnian, Serbian}}, {{t|sh|ра̀јчица|f}} {{qualifier|Croatian}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|paràdajz|m}} {{qualifier|Bosnian, Serbian}}, {{t+|sh|ràjčica|f}} {{qualifier|Croatian}}\n* Seychellois Creole: {{t|crs|tomat}}\n* Shor: {{t-needed|cjs}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|pumadoru|m}}, {{t+|scn|pummadoru|m}}, {{t+|scn|puma d'amuri|f}}, {{t+|scn|pumadamuri|f}}, {{t+|scn|pumu d'amuri|m}}, {{t+|scn|pumudamuri|m}}\n* Sinhalese: {{t|si|තක්‍කාලි}}\n* Slovak: {{t+|sk|paradajka|f}}, {{t|sk|rajčina|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|paradižnik|m}}\n* Sotho: {{t|st|tamati}}\n* Southern Altai: {{t|alt|помидор}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|tomate|m}}, {{t+|es|jitomate|m}}\n* Sranan Tongo: {{t|srn|tomati}}\n* Svan: {{t|sva|პა̈მიდორ}}, {{t|sva|პამინდორ}}, {{t|sva|პა̈ტრიჯან}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|nyanya}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|tomat|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|kamatis}}, {{t|tl|butinggan}}\n* Tajik: {{t+|tg|помидор}}\n* Tamil: {{t+|ta|தக்காளி}}\n* Taos: {{t|twf|tumą̀tiʼína}}\n* Tatar: {{t|tt|помидор}}, {{t|tt|томат}}\n* Telugu: {{t|te|మొలక్కాయ}}, {{t|te|టమోటా}}, {{q|Chittoor}} {{t|te|తక్కాలి}}, {{t|te|తక్కాలి పండు}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|มะเขือเทศ}}\n* Tigrinya: {{t|ti|ኮሚደረ}}\n* Tok Pisin: {{t+|tpi|tomato}}\n* Tumbuka: {{t|tum|mpwetekele}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|domates}}, {{t+|tr|pamidor}}, {{t+|tr|domat}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{t+|tr|banadura}}\n* Turkmen: {{t|tk|pomidor}}\n* Tuvan: {{t|tyv|помидор}}\n* Uab Meto: {{t|aoz|kauliman}}, {{t|aoz|kamati}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|помідо́р|m}}, {{t|uk|тома́т|m}} {{qualifier|usually processed}}\n* Unami: {{t|unm|skikopëlësh}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|ٹَماٹَر|m}}, {{t|ur|وِلایَتی بَین٘گَن|m}}, {{t|ur|بادَنْجانِ فَرَن٘گی|m}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|پەمىدۇر}}, {{t|ug|شوخلا}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|pomidor}}, {{t|uz|pomidorlar|p}}\n* Venetan: {{t|vec|pomidoro|m}}, {{t|vec|pomidor|m}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|cà chua}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|tomate|f}}, {{t+|wa|peme d' amour|f}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|tomato|m|f}}\n* Winnebago: {{t|win|wažąširiširik}}, {{t|win|wažą širiširic}}\n* Wolof: {{t+|wo|tamaate}}\n* Xhosa: {{t|xh|itumata|c9|c10}}\n* Yakut: {{t|sah|помидор}}, {{t|sah|томат}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|פּאָמידאָר|m}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|tòmátì}}\n* Zapotec:\n*: Isthmus Zapotec: {{t|zai|bichooxhe}}\n* Zhuang: {{t|za|makyungz}}, {{t|za|fanhgez}}\n* Zulu: {{t+|zu|utamatisi|c1a|c2a}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|color}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[tomaatti|tomaatin]][[punainen]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{en-adj}}\n\n# Of a shade of [[red]], the colour of a ripe tomato.\n#: {{color panel|FF6347}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Beverley Farmer|chapter=December|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=n3n-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT251|title=A Body of Water|location=Sydney, N.S.W.|publisher=w:Giramondo Publishing|year=1990|year_published=2020|isbn=978-1-925818-25-3|passage=Her face is on the cover: the Anne Estelle Rice portrait – or the black-eyed Japanese-bobbed head-and-shoulders bit of it – and the square-yoked dress is '''tomato''', or pomegranate, but ''never'' persimmon. If it stayed too long in the sun and faded, well yes, maybe then…}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Jackie Braun|chapter=Most Focused|title=Mr. Right There All Along|series=Harlequin Romance, #4258; The Fun Factor|location=Toronto, Ont.|publisher=[[w:Harlequin Enterprises|Harlequin]]|year=2011|page=220|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/mrrighttherealla0000brau/page/220/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-373-74117-5|passage=And she’d slathered a heavy layer of foundation over the raw skin of her face with the end result being a complexion that was more '''tomato''' than orange.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Jillian Cantor|title=Margot|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Riverhead Books|year=2013|pages=[https://archive.org/details/margot0000cant_s1j4/page/93/mode/1up 93–94] (chapter 16) and [https://archive.org/details/margot0000cant_s1j4/page/164/mode/1up 164] (chapter 26)|isbn=978-1-59448-643-2|passage=This afternoon, though, she saunters in, draped in a dress the color of a ripe tomato, with a hat to match, her hair twisted underneath in some kind of fashionable up-do that seems impossible to create oneself. {{...}} Penny is sitting there, on the bed, next to me, chewing on the end of the pen, dressed in her frivolous '''tomato''' dress.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Traci Andrighetti|chapter=9|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=-ypeEAAAQBAJ&pg=PT130|title=Valpolicella Violet|series=Franki Amato Mysteries|seriesvolume=7|publisher=Limoncello Press|year=2021|isbn=978-1-7355761-9-0|passage=Intending to tease out Shona’s know-it-all nature by spouting off some trivia, I googled the Pala d’Oro on my phone. It was pure folly, but I was kind of worried about her. “Wikipedia says the cloth has a hundred and eighty-seven enamel plaques depicting Christ and the saints that are decorated with gold, silver, and around two thousand gems.” I peeked at Shona, whose face was '''tomato''', and continued.}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|of the color of a ripe tomato}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[tomaatti|tomaatin]][[punainen]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive|rare}} to [[pelt]] with tomatoes\n# {{lb|en|transitive|rare}} to add tomatoes to (a dish)\n\n{{cln|en|nouns with irregular plurals}}\n{{c|en|Fruits|Tomatoes|Vegetables}}\n\n==Amis==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|ami|ja|-}} {{ja-r|トマト}}, from {{der|ami|en|tomato}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ami|noun}}\n\n# [[#English|tomato]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:ami:Dictionary of the Central Dialect of Amis|537900}}\n\n{{topic|ami|Fruits|Nightshades|Vegetables}}\n\n==Chichewa==\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|ny|en|tomato}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ny-IPA|tomáto}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ny-noun|tomáto|1a|-}}\n\n# {{l|en|tomato}}\n#: {{syn|ny|phwetekere|matimati}}\n\n{{topics|ny|Fruits}}\n\n==Esperanto==\n{{wp|eo:}}\n[[Image:Bright red tomato and cross section02.jpg|thumb|right]]\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|eo|ru|томат}}, {{der|eo|de|Tomate}}, {{der|eo|en|tomato}}, {{der|eo|fr|tomate}}, all from {{der|eo|es|tomate}}, from {{der|eo|nci|tomatl}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{eo-pr|a=LL-Q143 (epo)-Robin van der Vliet-tomato.wav;LL-Q143 (epo)-Lepticed7-tomato.wav}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{eo-head}}\n\n# {{l|en|tomato}} {{gl|fruit}}\n# tomato plant {{gl|{{taxfmt|Solanum lycopersicum|species}}}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|eo|tomata|pos=a|t=made of or related to tomatoes}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:eo:PIV 2020}}\n* {{R:eo:ReVo}}\n\n{{c|eo|Fruits|Vegetables|Tomatoes}}\n\n==Iban==\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|iba|en|tomato}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|iba|/tomato/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|iba|noun}}\n\n# {{l|en|tomato}}\n\n{{c|iba|Fruits|Vegetables}}\n\n==Ido==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{io-IPA}}\n* {{rhymes|io|ato}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{io-noun|tomat}}\n\n# {{l|en|tomato}}\n\n{{C|io|Foods}}\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|it|tomate}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|it|:bor|en:tomato}}\n{{bor+|it|en|tomato}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|it|LL-Q652 (ita)-DanielParoliere-tomato.wav}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{it-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|it|rare}} {{l|en|tomato}}\n#: {{syn|it|pomodoro}}\n# {{lb|it|informal}} {{l|en|ketchup}}\n\n==Japanese==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{ja-romaji}}\n\n# {{ja-romanization of|トマト}}\n\n==Swahili==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|sw|en|tomato}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|sw|Sw-ke-tomato.flac|a=Kenya}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sw-noun|n}}\n\n# [[#English|tomato]]\n#: {{syn|sw|nyanya}}\n#* {{quote-web|sw|date=16 December 2021|work=BBC News Swahili|url=https://www.bbc.com/swahili/habari-59678736|title=Wakenya wapata faraja mashambani baada ya corona kuwatimua mjini|text=Alianza kilimo cha malenge, mtama, '''tomato''' na sukuma wiki - na sasa anauza bidhaa zake katika soko la nyumbani.|t=He started cultivating pumpkin, millet, '''tomato''' and sukuma wiki - and now he sells his products in the domestic market.}}\n\n{{C|sw|Vegetables}}\n\n==Tok Pisin==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|tpi|en|tomato}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tpi|noun}}\n\n# {{l|en|tomato}}\n#* {{quote-book\n|tpi\n|year=1995\n|author=John Verhaar\n|title=Toward a reference grammar of Tok Pisin: an experiment in corpus linguistics\n|chapter=\n|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=4DeKkIzS8B4C&pg=PA433#v=onepage&q&f=false\n|isbn=0-8248-1672-2\n|page=433\n|passage=Mekim olsem pinis, orait tupela i planim taro na banana, na kumu, painap, kon, '''tomato''', na kaukau tu.}}\n\n{{c|tpi|Fruits|Nightshades|Vegetables}}\n\n==Welsh==\n{{swp|cy:}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|cy|en|tomato}}, from {{der|cy|es|tomate}}, from {{der|cy|nci|tomatl}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|cy|/tɔˈmatɔ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{cy-noun|m|tomatoes}}\n\n# {{l|en|tomato}}\n#: {{syn|cy|afal cariad}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|cy|tomato bach melys|t=cherry tomato}}\n\n===Mutation===\n{{cy-mut}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:cy:GPC}}\n\n{{c|cy|Fruits|Nightshades|Vegetables}}"}}